From our analysis, we identify a possible long-term trend. However, such a long-term signal could be due both to a planetary companion or to stellar magnetic activity, and additional data of ESPRESSO-like precision covering a longer baseline are needed to understand its nature. This possible additional signal could also be the source of the slight discrepancy in the mass of TOI-406 b when using ESPRESSO-only data or all the available RVs.
The quasi-periodic GP modelling of the RVs and dLW results in the detection of a clear periodicity at Prot = 29.2 ± 0.5 days (see Fig. 11). This signal matches the period identified also in the ASAS-SN light curves and (marginally) in the TESS photometry (Sect. 5.2). We attribute
